Abstract
This document describes data types and formats that should be shared by the Neurofibromatosis (NF) research community for the NF Data Portal.
Introduction
The NF Data Portal is a collaborative data-sharing platform for Neurofibromatosis, a rare genetic disease. It has been jointly supported by multiple funding organizations â the Gilbert Family Foundation (GFF), Childrenâs Tumor Foundation (CTF), Neurofibromatosis Therapeutic Acceleration Program (NTAP), NCI Developmental and Hyperactive Ras Tumor SPORE (DHART SPORE), CDMRP Neurofibromatosis Research Program (CDMRP NFRP), and Neurofibromatosis Research Initiative (NFRI) â and therefore represents substantial NF research activity.
As the NF community may continue to expand to add new affiliated or independent researchers, and therefore new data, having these standards will help maintain the quality and quantity of our valuable resources. But also important is that this document should actually benefit our data contributors.  One advantage is allowing our contributors to prioritize submissions accordingly. The burden of having to submit data in multiple formats can also be avoided, since preferred formats are clear. These specifications should lead to higher-impact data, leaning towards the most interoperabe formats that make data more likely to be reused (and cited). Finally, this open document lets our community be apprised of the status quo, including specifications currently not included, so that they can continue to provide comments.
These current data-sharing specifications have been informed by several sources. First are requirements already established by our funding organizations, which are largely non-negotiable. Second is the feedback received from the community, which was especially influential for data types outside of what is required by default, i.e.Â more âoptionalâ data types. This feedback was solicited from the research community through an open RFC, from which results are incorporated here. Lastly, journal requirements and other repositories also had some influence on these specifications.
Data types and formats summary
Table 1 summarizes specifications for common data types that are of interest for the NF community. These standards should apply for most general cases. However, we do note that for some data types, the community comments provided additional considerations that serve to qualify or supplement what is in this table. Community results are also summarized in Quantified Results section.


